From Brent Williams Subject Re Colorado Jumbo for Gateway Peter F Davis writes I've just installed a new Colorado Jumbo tape backup unit from Gateway and I have a couple of complaints with I don't know how common or serious these problems may I would appreciate some feedback from others who have used this BTW This is on a tower I have a similar configuration Colorado on DX The problems are o Firstly Gateway shipped me only Mb tapes even though the drive is a Mb When I called to complain they only said That's all we carry and With compression you can fit Mb on one Maybe so but then why did I pay extra for the large capacity tape drive You got suckered in the same way I Silly me believing that the logo on the front meant actual carrying The people who do this sort of thing for a living call it Lawyers who prosecute it call it Perhaps we can have a bunch of other duped buyers march on their corporate o I have about Mb of data on my C I choose the space optimizing compression scheme and started a full The software estimated it would take about It took Does this sound about right This is a bit My system takes about minutes to do the same Usually hours particularly if the tape is grinding away the whole time means that your block size for the write is too Is there any way to change the block size or write buffer size so it's bigger o During the backup about a dozen files came up with access denied Most of these were in C WINDOWS SYSTEM but also C WINDOWS and a couple of files in the C TAPE Anyone else had this happen This is because the files are opened by The files in the TAPE directory are likely the executable file or the configuration file for the tape I would recommend running the backup from DOS so it will make a complete backup of the TAPE Thanks for any and all feedback on this I'd also appreciate hearing of good sources for blank tape cartridges preferably Mb The cartridges won't do you any good since the drive won't write of physical data on the pd brent william